Evidence 19 claims that an eyewitness saw the Professor resurrect from his grave on the night of his execution. Meanwhile, in Testimony 2, Tusspells states that he took a mould of the Professor’s head in the cemetery just before the corpse was interred—implying a conventional burial with no hint of the corpse returning to life. This creates a direct contradiction: if the body was indeed interred as described, there would be no opportunity for a resurrection to be witnessed as claimed in Evidence 19.

{"evidence": 19, "testimony": 2}

Testimony 4 by Drebber states, “There was no gunshot from behind me at all. Nor any splattering blood.” However, Evidence 17—the Post-Explosion Photograph—shows clear blood traces dripping down from the chest, which contradicts his claim that there was no splattering blood.

{"evidence": 17, "testimony": 4}

Testimony 3 asserts that the victim’s death was caused solely by the neck trauma from a thirty‐foot fall, yet Evidence 5 – the Photograph of the Victim – clearly shows an apparent stab wound to the chest. This discrepancy between a fall-induced neck injury and a visible chest wound creates an inconsistency between the testimony and the evidence.
